                        <additions>
                            <list>
                                <item xml:id="e1">
                                    <desc>Scribal practices are difficult to observe due to the bad condition of the manuscript, whose text is mostly illegible.</desc>
                                </item>
                                
                                <item xml:id="e2">
                                    <desc> The name of the original owner, <persName ref="PRS13686WaldaTH"/>, is written in various supplication formulas. It is fully readable on <locus target="#31v"/>
                                        and partially legible on <locus from="23r" to="23v"/> (where only Walda is legible) and on <locus target="#28r"/> (where only Walda Takla is legible).</desc>
                                </item>
                               
                                <item xml:id="e3">
                                    <locus target="#2v"/>
                                    <desc>Illegible writings in black ink, possibly in the main hand. The ink is almost completely faded out.</desc>
                                </item>

                                <item xml:id="e4">
                                    <desc>A white sticker is glued to the inner side of the front board. The name of <persName ref="PRS5782JuelJen"/> is printed on it
                                        (‘<foreign xml:lang="gez">ቤንት፡ ዩውል፡ የንሰን።</foreign>’) and the signature ‘MS. Aeth. g. 30’ is written in pencil below it.
                                        An additional sticker, with the signature ‘Ms 7’ on it, is also glued to the inner side of the front board.
                                        The textual content and dating of the book (‘Ethiopic Prayers C 20’) is indicated in pencil in the inner side of the front board.
                                    </desc>
                                </item>
                            </list>
                        </additions>

                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="true Ethiopian">
                                <decoNote xml:id="b1" type="bindingMaterial">
                                  The book is bound in <material key="wood">wooden</material> boards.
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="Boards">
                                  The boards are flush with the bookblock and have shallow external bevels. The grain runs vertically.
                                  The external surface of the boards is polished and a finishing layer of dark colour was added. The inner surface and the edges are rough.
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b4" type="Sewing">
                                  Chainstitch sewing on two sewing stations (one pair); Z-plied thread.
                                  In the first quire, between the sewing stations, there is one length of thread. In the rest of the quires there are double lengths.
                                  The sewing is closed in the last quire, by knotting the ends of the thread to each other.
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b5" type="SewingStations">2</decoNote>

                                <decoNote xml:id="b6" type="Spine">
                                  The small holes close to the head of the quires are probably what remains of quire tackets.
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b7" type="SlipCase">
                                  The manuscript is provided with a reddish-brown leather two-piece slip case. The case consists of two halves that fit together to
                                  enclose the manuscript. One half is fitted on the head edge, the other on the tail edge. The case presents a blind-tooled decoration
                                  featuring a frame in which <term key="singleStraightLine">single straight lines</term> cross each other forming a St Andrew cross.
                                </decoNote>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
